Aim
To write a C++ program that demonstrates unary operator overloading using a class.

Algorithm
Start the program.
Create a class with data members.
Define a constructor to initialize the data.
Overload a unary operator (such as ++, --, or unary -).
Inside the operator function, modify the objectâ€™s data.
Create object(s) in main().
Apply the unary operator to the object.
Display the values before and after overloading.
End the program.

Program (C++)
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;
class Number {
    int x;

public:
    // Constructor
    Number(int a) {
        x = a;
    }

    // Unary operator overloading for ++
    void operator++() {
        x = x + 1;
    }

    // Unary operator overloading for -
    void operator-() {
        x = -x;
    }

    // Display function
    void display() {
        cout << "Value of x: " << x << endl;
    }
};

int main() {
    Number n(10);

    cout << "Initial Value:" << endl;
    n.display();

    // Calling overloaded ++ operator
    ++n;

    cout << "\nAfter Applying ++ Operator:" << endl;
    n.display();

    // Calling overloaded unary - operator
    -n;

    cout << "\nAfter Applying Unary - Operator:" << endl;
    n.display();

    return 0;
}

Sample Output (Result)
Initial Value:
Value of x: 10

After Applying ++ Operator:
Value of x: 11

After Applying Unary - Operator:
Value of x: -11

Result
Thus, the program successfully demonstrates the use of unary operator overloading in C++.
